    MANUFACTURING AND FABRICATION (MASS PRODUCTION LOGIC)
    10.1. CMOS Compatibility: IPIC is designed for 300mm Silicon-on-Insulator (SOI) wafers. The photonic layer is fabricated as a "Front-End-of-Line" (FEOL) or "Back-End-of-Line" (BEOL) addition, allowing integration with standard foundry processes at TSMC, Intel, or GlobalFoundries.
    10.2. Multi-Layer Photonic Stacking: Utilizing Through-Silicon Vias (TSV) and hybrid bonding to stack the photonic compute die directly on top of a high-speed HBM3e memory controller.
    10.3. Heterogeneous Integration: The laser source (InP - Indium Phosphide) is flip-chip bonded or heterogeneously integrated onto the silicon substrate to minimize coupling losses (<0.5 dB).
    SOFTWARE STACK AND IPIC-API (THE COMPILER LAYER)
    11.1. Radiant-OS Interface: A low-level driver that maps neural network tensors directly to MZI phase settings.
    11.2. Photonic Graph Compiler: Automatically decomposes complex matrices into U(2) unitary rotations optimized for the IPIC mesh topology.
    11.3. Framework Integration: Native support for PyTorch and TensorFlow via a custom "IPIC-Backend" plugin. Users can run standard models (e.g., Llama-3, Claude-4) by simply switching the device target to 'device=ipic'.
    11.4. Real-Time Weight Loading: Utilizing a high-speed DMA (Direct Memory Access) engine to update the MZI-mesh phases at sub-microsecond intervals for dynamic inference.

